This is a known breaking change. In .NET 10, MAUI adopted **edge-to-edge** rendering on Android by default, and `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` (deprecated since Android API 30) no longer drives layout changes.

Here's what to do:

### 1. Set `adjustResize` in `AndroidManifest.xml`

In `Platforms/Android/AndroidManifest.xml`, add (or update) the `windowSoftInputMode` on your main activity:

```xml
<activity
    ...
    android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize" />
```

### 2. Use keyboard-aware insets in your layout

With edge-to-edge, your page needs to **react to window insets**. The simplest approach is to keep MAUI's built-in `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` enabled (it's on by default). For a chat screen, structure your page like this:

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0"
                    ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}"
                    ItemsUpdatingScrollMode="KeepLastItemInView" />

    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..."
               HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

### 3. If auto-scroll isn't enough, handle insets manually

On the Android platform, you can listen for IME (keyboard) insets and adjust bottom padding:

```csharp
// In Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.ApplicationModel;

public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(
            Window!.DecorView.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!,
            new KeyboardInsetsListener());
    }

    private class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Use the larger of IME or nav bar bottom inset
            int bottomPx = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);

            // Convert to device-independent pixels and apply
            double bottomDp = bottomPx / (double)v.Resources!.DisplayMetrics!.Density;

            MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(() =>
            {
                if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is ContentPage page)
                    page.Padding = new Thickness(0, 0, 0, bottomDp);
            });

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

### TL;DR

| .NET 9 | .NET 10 |
|---|---|
| `UseWindowSoftInputModeAdjust(Resize)` | `adjustResize` in manifest + edge-to-edge insets |

The manifest flag tells Android to resize the window, and edge-to-edge insets ensure your layout actually reflows to account for the keyboard. For most chat layouts, the built-in `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` + a `Grid` with `Auto`-sized bottom row is sufficient.
